Francisco Sanchez-Saez

Published

June 11, 2023

6.1 Input

The table to be analysed is mbds.csv.

6.2 Check variables

The variables extracted from mbds are: sip, fecha_ingreso, fecha_alta, dpto_cod, hosp_cod, serv_ing_cod, serv_ing_desc, tipo_activ, circ_ing_cod, circ_ing_desc, circ_alta_cod, circ_alta_desc, d1, d2, d3, d4, d5, d6, d7, d8, d9, d10, d11, d12, d13, d14, d15, d16, d17, d18, d19, d20, d21, d22, d23, d24, d25, d26, d27, d28, d29, d30, p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, p7, p8, p9, p10, p11, p12, p13, p14, p15, p16, p17, p18, p19, p20, p21, p22, p23, p24, p25, p26, p27, p28, p29, p30, tipo_codigo, fecha_parto, parto_multiple, semana_gest, peso1, sexo1, peso2, sexo2, peso3, sexo3, ind_uci, and estancias_uci.

6.2.1 Check mandatory vars

All mandatory vars are present.

6.2.2 Check all vars

dpto_desc and hosp_desc were not extracted.

6.2.3 Completeness

In Figure 6.1 is shown the percentage of non-missing values for each variable. Non-mandatory variables are shown at the bottom of the figure.



6.3 Check content

The mbds table has a total of n = 1 ‍181 ‍384 observations.

6.3.1 Population

  • In mbds table there are 605 ‍156 distinct individuals. All the individuals are included in the target population. Therefore, there are 605 ‍156 individuals included in the target population out of the 1 ‍842 ‍818 total individuals in the cohort. These represents 32.84% of the total.
  • The Table 7.1 shows the number of individuals per year of the study period.
